did.unittitle: Harold and Joyce Pomeroy Schwartz Public Art Archive
did.abstract: The Harold and Joyce Pomeroy Schwartz Public Art Archive documents the work of public arts administrator and consultant Joyce Pomeroy Schwartz. The collection consists of Schwartz's professional records, pertaining to her involvement with Pace Gallery and Works of Art for Public Spaces, Ltd. This collection includes artist biographies, invitations and exhibition information, photographic materials, reviews and promotional materials, professional correspondence, administrative files, financial records, contracts, and project proposals.
did.physloc: Materials are stored offsite and advance notice is required for use. Please request materials at least two business days prior to your research visit to coordinate access.

bioghist.head: Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Joyce Pomeroy Schwartz grew up in Brooklyn, New York. She received her BA in English Literature and American History from Hunter College, and her MA in Art Education at New York University. Soon after, Schwartz became involved in both the political and art scenes in New York City, sparking her interest in art in a public context.

In 1967, Schwartz opened and managed a gallery specializing in fine art photography called "The Photographer's Gallery" until its closing in 1971. In 1979, she helped found ArtTable, a group of women dedicated to talking about the role of women in the art world. From 1973 to 1981, she worked as the Director of Commissions at Pace Gallery, developing programs in public art and architecture.

In 1982, Schwartz became the president of Works of Art for Public Spaces Ltd., a consulting firm in contemporary art focusing on architecture and landscape. Schwartz continues to direct the firm, curate exhibitions and write critically about public art.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: The Harold and Joyce Pomeroy Schwartz Public Art Archive consists of the professional records of Joyce Pomeroy Schwartz, pertaining to her involvement with Pace Gallery and Works of Art for Public Spaces, Ltd.

The collection spans from 1961 to 2009, covering her career as an artist, director at Pace, and president of Works of Art for Public Spaces, Ltd. Much of the material coincides with Schwartz's work as the Director of Commissions at Pace, where she started to focus on developing public art with artists in New York City. Works of Art for Public Spaces, Ltd., a consulting firm in contemporary art, continues to combine art in architecture and the public sphere in several cities across the country and abroad. This collection documents the work of Joyce Pomeroy Schwartz as an artist and art critic, as well as a commissioner and consultant for major art organizations.

The collection includes artist biographies, invitations and exhibition information, photographs and slides, reviews and promotional materials, professional correspondence, administrative files, financial records, contracts, and project proposals.
Further scope and content description is found at the beginning of each series.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This collection is arranged into the following series:

list.head: Missing Title
list.item: Series I: Artists Files includes artist biographies, photographic materials, invitations, promotional materials, exhibition information, and reviews. This series is arranged alphabetically by artist's last name.

Series II: Administrative Files includes personal and professional correspondence, contracts, financial records, and project proposals. This series is arranged alphabetically by artist's last name, project title, or location.
Series III: Data Storage includes digital portfolios and other electronic media, and is arranged alphabetically by artist's last name.

Series IV: Video includes supplemental audiovisual material and minimal audio material from both artists and organizations. It is arranged alphabetically by last name or, in the absence of a name, by title.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Open to researchers. Appointments are necessary for the use of manuscript and archival Materials are open to researchers. Please contact the Fales Library and Special Collections, fales.library@nyu.edu, 212-998-2596.collections.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Copyright (or related rights to publicity and privacy) for materials in this collection was not transferred to New York University. Permission to use materials must be secured from the copyright holder. Please contact the Fales Library and Special Collections, fales.library@nyu.edu, 212-998-2596.

acqinfo.head: Provenance
acqinfo.p: The Harold and Joyce Pomeroy Schwartz Public Art Archive was donated to NYU's Fales Library and Special Collections in two batches, in 2005 and 2009.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p:
Published citations should take the following form:
Identification of item, date (if known); Harold and Joyce Pomeroy Schwartz Public Art Archive; MSS 171; box number; folder number; Fales Library and Special Collections, New York University Libraries.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Material at Fales Library and Special Collections
relatedmaterial.p: New Museum Library Lucy Lippard Collection (MSS.169)

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Materials
separatedmaterial.p: The books that were donated with this collection will be catalogued and made available in Bobcat at a later date.

phystech.head: Physical Characteristics and Technical Requirements
phystech.p: Born-digital and audiovisual materials have not been preserved and may not be available to researchers.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Decisions regarding arrangement, description, and physical interventions for this collection prior to 2019 have not yet been recorded. In February 2019 materials from Box 65 were prepared to be sent offsite. Loose documents were placed in archival folders and given titles. All materials were kept in their original order in the box.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Series I: Artists Files represents Schwartz's subject files for individual artists. The files include artist biographies, photographic materials, invitations, promotional materials, exhibition information, and reviews. This series is arranged alphabetically by artist's last name. When Schwartz had multiple files for a single artist, those files were retained rather than being combined.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Materials
separatedmaterial.p: Compact disks in this series were removed to Series III: Data Storage.

compact disk: Elemental Spring: Guangzhou, Elemental Spring: Hangzhou, Ink Rock Water, Elemental Spring: Shenzhen Project, Wind/Weed Wind/Water, Nectar for Neptune Barbara Edelstein

CD cover booklet: Barbara Edelstein, a native of Los Angeles, was exposed to the cultures of both shores of the Pacific in her early years. The geographical proximity and cultural blending of the Asian and the American traditions had a significant impact on her way of thinking, and later cultivated in her a unique style of Zen artistry. Barbara's artworks continually reflect water as both a concrete material and an abstract concept - a dualism that bridges the natural and the artistic worlds. The flow of water in her artworks communicates a motion that transcends time, an elevation of spirituality, and a delicate form of expression that is the epitome of feminism. "The environment plays a large part in how I formulate my work. I have strived to unite nature and the metropolitan culture in a graceful balance... I put into my artworks both the products of nature and processed materials. The purpose is to recreate a new kind of harmony in which the spirit of nature is eternal." Thus, one may speculate that Barbara's artworks are the extensions of nature, or that nature has become an integral component of her artistic expression.
